<ToolLayout
  title="Markdown to HTML Converter | Webutilbox"
  description="Convert Markdown text to HTML instantly with live preview. Supports GitHub-Flavored Markdown. Free online Markdown to HTML converter and previewer."
  canonical={canonical}
  ogImage="https://webutilbox.com/assets/og/og-developer.svg"
  keywords="markdown to html, markdown converter, md to html, markdown preview, github markdown"
  h1="📝 Markdown to HTML Converter"
  subtitle="Convert Markdown to HTML with live preview."
  lastUpdated=""
  shareText="Free%20online%20Markdown%20to%20HTML%20Converter%20%7C%20Webutilbox%20on%20Webutilbox.%20Privacy-focused%2C%20runs%20100%25%20in%20your%20browser."
  shareUrl={canonical}
  embedUrl={canonical}
  embedTitle="Markdown to HTML Converter -- Webutilbox"
  embedHeight={600}
  toolCss={true}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>






<div class="workspace">
    <div class="md-grid">

        <!-- Left: Markdown Input -->
        <div class="md-col">
            <div class="md-panel-header">
                <span class="md-panel-title">📝 Markdown Input</span>
                <div style="display:flex; gap:8px;">
                    <button id="loadBtn" class="btn btn-secondary btn-sm">Load Sample</button>
                </div>
            </div>
            <textarea id="markdownInput"
                placeholder="# Hello World&#10;&#10;Type your **Markdown** here and see the live preview..."
                style="height:460px; font-family:'Courier New',monospace; font-size:0.85rem; resize:vertical; line-height:1.6;">
            </textarea>
        </div>

        <!-- Right: Preview + HTML Output -->
        <div class="md-col">
            <div class="md-panel-header">
                <div class="md-output-tabs">
                    <button id="previewTab" class="md-tab md-tab-active">👁️ Preview</button>
                    <button id="htmlTab" class="md-tab">&lt;/&gt; HTML</button>
                </div>
                <button id="copyBtn" class="btn btn-success btn-sm">Copy HTML</button>
            </div>

            <!-- Rendered preview -->
            <div id="previewDiv" class="md-preview-pane">
                <div style="color:var(--gray); text-align:center; padding:60px 20px; font-size:0.85rem;">
                    Enter Markdown to see preview...
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Raw HTML output -->
            <textarea id="htmlOutput" style="display:none; height:460px; font-family:'Courier New',monospace; font-size:0.82rem;" readonly placeholder="Generated HTML will appear here..."></textarea>
        </div>

    </div>
</div>

<style is:global>
.md-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: 22px;
    align-items: start;
}
.md-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
}
.md-panel-header {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: center;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}
.md-panel-title {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--white);
}
.md-output-tabs {
    display: flex;
    gap: 6px;
}
.md-tab {
    padding: 5px 14px;
    background: var(--dark);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 6px;
    color: var(--gray);
    cursor: pointer;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    transition: all 0.2s;
}
.md-tab:hover { color: var(--white); border-color: var(--primary); }
.md-tab-active {
    background: var(--primary);
    border-color: var(--primary);
    color: var(--white);
}
.md-preview-pane {
    height: 460px;
    overflow-y: auto;
    background: #fff;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 20px 24px;
    color: #1a1a1a;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    resize: vertical;
}
.btn-sm {
    padding: 5px 12px;
    font-size: 0.82rem;
}
@media (max-width: 768px) {
    .md-grid {
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
        gap: 20px;
    }
}
</style>


<script defer src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/marked@11.1.1/marked.min.js"></script>
<script src="/js/markdown-to-html.js" defer></script>

<div class="info-section" slot="info">
<h2>Markdown to HTML Converter - Instant Live Preview</h2>
        <p>Our free Markdown to HTML Converter lets you write Markdown and instantly see the rendered HTML output side by side. Whether you're a developer, blogger, or technical writer, this tool eliminates the guesswork from Markdown formatting and gives you clean, ready-to-use HTML code in seconds.</p>

        <h3>What Is Markdown to HTML Conversion?</h3>
        <p>Markdown is a lightweight markup language designed to be easy to read and write in plain text. It uses simple symbols like asterisks, hashes, and brackets to define formatting. When you convert Markdown to HTML, those symbols are transformed into proper HTML tags — headings become &lt;h1&gt;–&lt;h6&gt;, bold text becomes &lt;strong&gt;, links become &lt;a&gt; tags, and so on.</p>
        <p>This converter uses the popular <strong>marked.js</strong> library with GitHub Flavored Markdown (GFM) support, which means it handles tables, fenced code blocks, strikethrough, and task lists — all the extras you'd expect from modern Markdown rendering.</p>
        <p>The live preview updates as you type, so you can see exactly how your content will look in a browser without switching between tools or running a build process.</p>

        <h3>Markdown Conversion Options</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Real-time live preview that updates as you type</li>
            <li>GitHub Flavored Markdown (GFM) support including tables and task lists</li>
            <li>Fenced code blocks with syntax highlighting-ready output</li>
            <li>Toggle between rendered preview and raw HTML output</li>
            <li>One-click copy of the generated HTML to clipboard</li>
            <li>Load sample Markdown to explore the tool instantly</li>
            <li>Fully client-side — no server, no uploads, no account needed</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>How to Use the Markdown to HTML Converter</h3>
        <p>Getting started is straightforward. Just paste or type your Markdown in the left panel and watch the preview update on the right in real time.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Step 1: Type or paste your Markdown content into the left text area.</li>
            <li>Step 2: Watch the live preview render your formatted content on the right.</li>
            <li>Step 3: Click the "HTML" tab to switch from the visual preview to the raw HTML source.</li>
            <li>Step 4: Click "Copy HTML" to copy the generated HTML to your clipboard.</li>
            <li>Step 5: Paste the HTML directly into your website, CMS, or email template.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Writing and Converting Markdown</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Converting README files to HTML for embedding in web pages or documentation sites</li>
            <li>Writing blog posts in Markdown and exporting clean HTML for your CMS</li>
            <li>Generating HTML email content from Markdown drafts</li>
            <li>Previewing Markdown documentation before publishing to GitHub or GitLab</li>
            <li>Teaching Markdown syntax to students or new developers with instant visual feedback</li>
            <li>Quickly prototyping formatted content without writing HTML by hand</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Markdown Formatting Best Practices</h3>
        <p>When writing Markdown for HTML output, keep your structure clean. Use a single <code>#</code> for your main heading and <code>##</code> for subsections — this maps directly to proper semantic HTML heading hierarchy, which is important for both readability and SEO.</p>
        <p>For code blocks, always use triple backticks with a language identifier (e.g., <code>```javascript</code>) rather than indented code. This produces a <code>&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class="language-javascript"&gt;</code> block that works seamlessly with syntax highlighting libraries like Prism.js or highlight.js.</p>
        <p>If you're pasting the output into a CMS or email builder, check that the tool doesn't strip certain tags. Some platforms sanitize HTML and remove elements like <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;table&gt;</code>. In those cases, simplify your Markdown to avoid complex structures.</p>

        

        <h3>Markdown Converted Locally in Browser</h3>
        <p>Conversion runs in your browser. Your Markdown content never leaves your device.</p>
        
            <h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
            <div class="faq-list">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What Markdown syntax is supported?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>The converter supports standard CommonMark syntax: headings (#), bold (**text**), italic (*text*), links ([text](url)), images (![alt](url)), code blocks (```), inline code (`code`), blockquotes (>), ordered and unordered lists, horizontal rules (---), and tables.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I use HTML inside my Markdown?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Standard Markdown allows raw HTML to be mixed in. HTML tags in your Markdown will be passed through to the output. This is useful for elements Markdown does not support natively, like colored text or custom div containers.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why does my code block not show syntax highlighting?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>This converter outputs standard HTML with code blocks wrapped in pre and code tags. Syntax highlighting requires a separate library like Prism.js or highlight.js to be added to the page where you use the output.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">How do I create a table in Markdown?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Use pipes and hyphens: | Header 1 | Header 2 | on the first line, | --- | --- | on the second line (the separator), then | Cell 1 | Cell 2 | for each row. Align columns by adding colons to the separator: | :--- | for left, | ---: | for right, | :---: | for center.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I convert the HTML back to Markdown?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>This tool converts Markdown to HTML only. For the reverse (HTML to Markdown), you would need a separate tool. If you need to round-trip content, keep your original Markdown source and regenerate the HTML whenever needed.</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>

